ire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Dryslwyn, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Dryslwyn, Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk",",Carmarthenshire,,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"August 1425–1492":"August 1425–1492","1425–1492":"1425–1492","–Male":"Deceased","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1451–1545":"1451–1545","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1425":"1425","1545":"1545","1400":"1400","1451":"1451","before 1450":"before 1450","1450":"1450","1492":"1492","August 1425":"August 1425","1449":"1449","Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Dryslwyn, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Dryslwyn, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom",",Carmarthenshire,,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: Welsh forms of William."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwyllim","meanings":["Welsh: Welsh forms of William."]},{"name":"Gwyllym","meanings":["Welsh: Welsh forms of William."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry Ap Gwilym apGwilym Knight de Court was born in August 1425, in Llangathen, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Gwylim ap Thomas \"Fychan\", was 26 and his mother, Gwladys ferch Jonhn, was 26. He married Mabli ferch Gwilym of Ystradffin Llanfairarybryn in 1449, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. His occupation is listed as builder of court henry near dryslwyn castle in llangathen parish in Court Henry, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom. He died in 1492, in Dryslwyn, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"August 1425–1492":"august 1425–1492","1425–1492":"1425–1492","–Male":"Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1451–